Pandav Leni (Pandav Caves), Nashik is one of the most fascinating and well-preserved historical sites in the city. These ancient Buddhist rock-cut caves date back more than 2,000 years and showcase beautiful carvings, inscriptions, and sculptures that reflect the rich cultural and spiritual heritage of Nashik.
The caves are located on a hill, and visitors need to climb a series of steps to reach them. The trek is moderately easy, and the climb offers a refreshing experience with panoramic views of Nashik city, especially during sunrise and sunset. The atmosphere is peaceful, making it a perfect blend of history, spirituality, and nature.
Inside the caves, the detailed stone carvings, prayer halls (chaityas), and monasteries (viharas) give a glimpse of Buddhist architecture and life from centuries ago. The site is well maintained, with basic facilities, signboards, and guides available for those interested in deeper historical insights.
Parking is available at the base, and small stalls serve refreshments. It’s advisable to wear comfortable shoes, carry water, and visit during morning or evening hours to avoid the midday heat.
Overall, Pandav Leni is a must-visit in Nashik for history lovers, travelers, and anyone seeking a peaceful and enriching experience. It’s not just a tourist spot but a journey back into ancient India’s cultural past.

Stepping into the ancient serenity of Pandav Leni Caves in the crisp morning air was an incredibly refreshing experience. Pandav Leni, near Nashik, is a captivating complex of 24 ancient rock-cut caves dating from the 1st century BCE to the 2nd century CE. Carved into Trirashmi Hill, most served as Buddhist viharas, with Cave 18 as a chaitya hall. Standouts like Caves 3, 10, and 18 feature ornate pilasters, stupas, and detailed sculptural panels of Buddha, Bodhisattvas, and Jain figures  ￼. Accessible via a 20‑minute uphill climb, the site also includes ancient water cisterns and inscriptions revealing donations from Satavahana and Western Kshatrapa dynasties  ￼. A serene, historic treasure offering panoramic views and a profound glimpse into India’s early rock-cut architecture and religious heritage.

Shree Navshya Ganpati Mandir is one of the most revered and historic temples in Nashik, located peacefully on the banks of the Godavari River. The atmosphere here is calming, spiritual, and perfect for anyone seeking divine blessings or a break from daily chaos.

Temple History:
This ancient temple is believed to be over 300 years old, built during the Peshwa era. The temple was originally constructed by the royal family of Peshwas, especially by Raghoba Dada and his wife Anandibai. The idol of Lord Ganpati here is known as Navshya Ganpati, meaning the one who answers all prayers ("Navas" = wishes). Devotees from all over Maharashtra and beyond come to offer prayers, believing their genuine wishes will be fulfilled here.

Bell-Tying Ritual:
One of the unique traditions of this temple is the bell-tying ritual. Devotees who have their wishes fulfilled return to the temple and tie a brass bell as a token of gratitude. You can see hundreds of bells tied around the temple premises, which gives the place a truly divine and powerful aura. Each bell represents a fulfilled prayer – a symbol of faith, hope, and devotion.

Riverside Serenity:
The temple's location right beside the Godavari River adds to the spiritual ambiance. Many visitors sit by the riverside after darshan to meditate, relax, or simply enjoy the peaceful flow of the river.

Nashik, a city steeped in history and culture, is not just known for its sacred temples and vibrant vineyards; it also boasts a thriving architectural scene that reflects its unique character. From the ancient Shree Navshya Ganpati Mandir, nestled along the banks of the Godavari River, to the modern designs of local firms, the city is a canvas where tradition meets innovation. Each structure tells a story, whether it’s the understated elegance of the Shree Kapaleshwar Mahadev Mandir or the contemporary flair of architects like Durgesh R. Khade, who seamlessly blend modern aesthetics with traditional Indian elements.

As you wander through Nashik, you’ll discover a diverse array of architectural styles that cater to various tastes and needs. Firms like Deore Dhamne Architects and Milieu Casa Architects are redefining the skyline with their commitment to quality and functionality, while hidden gems like Gulve Architects focus on creating beautiful bungalows that enhance the local landscape. The Wanderlog team is passionate about uncovering these architectural treasures, and we invite you to explore the remarkable designs that make Nashik a true architectural delight.

I recently visited the Pandav Leni Caves and had a fantastic time. It's an incredible historical site with a serene and spiritual atmosphere. The caves are beautifully carved and the intricate details are just amazing to see up close. The hike up is a bit steep, but it's well worth the effort for the stunning views of Nashik from the top. The site is clean and well-maintained, and there are plenty of spots to sit and reflect. It's a must-visit for anyone interested in history, architecture, or just looking for a peaceful escape. Pandav Leni (Pandav Caves), Nashik is one of the most fascinating and well-preserved historical sites in the city. These ancient Buddhist rock-cut caves date back more than 2,000 years and showcase beautiful carvings, inscriptions, and sculptures that reflect the rich cultural and spiritual heritage of Nashik.
The caves are located on a hill, and visitors need to climb a series of steps to reach them. The trek is moderately easy, and the climb offers a refreshing experience with panoramic views of Nashik city, especially during sunrise and sunset. The atmosphere is peaceful, making it a perfect blend of history, spirituality, and nature.
Inside the caves, the detailed stone carvings, prayer halls (chaityas), and monasteries (viharas) give a glimpse of Buddhist architecture and life from centuries ago. The site is well maintained, with basic facilities, signboards, and guides available for those interested in deeper historical insights.
Parking is available at the base, and small stalls serve refreshments. It’s advisable to wear comfortable shoes, carry water, and visit during morning or evening hours to avoid the midday heat.
Overall, Pandav Leni is a must-visit in Nashik for history lovers, travelers, and anyone seeking a peaceful and enriching experience. It’s not just a tourist spot but a journey back into ancient India’s cultural past.

Stepping into the ancient serenity of Pandav Leni Caves in the crisp morning air was an incredibly refreshing experience. The early light beautifully illuminated the intricate rock-cut sculptures, revealing details often missed later in the day. From the hilltop, the expansive views of Nashik, still waking up under the gentle morning sun, were simply breathtaking and offered a profound sense of peace and history.

Pandav Leni, near Nashik, is a captivating complex of 24 ancient rock-cut caves dating from the 1st century BCE to the 2nd century CE. Carved into Trirashmi Hill, most served as Buddhist viharas, with Cave 18 as a chaitya hall. Standouts like Caves 3, 10, and 18 feature ornate pilasters, stupas, and detailed sculptural panels of Buddha, Bodhisattvas, and Jain figures  ￼. Accessible via a 20‑minute uphill climb, the site also includes ancient water cisterns and inscriptions revealing donations from Satavahana and Western Kshatrapa dynasties  ￼. A serene, historic treasure offering panoramic views and a profound glimpse into India’s early rock-cut architecture and religious heritage.

reviews.reviewText:
My visit to Sula Vineyard was a refreshing change from the usual city pace. Even though I don’t drink alcohol, I found the place surprisingly enjoyable and worth the experience. The lush greenery, expansive vineyard views, and the calm, open-air vibe gave it a serene, vacation-like feel. It’s the kind of place where time slows down just enough for you to soak in the moment.

I spent most of my time strolling around the vineyard and clicking pictures—the landscape is picture-perfect, especially around sunset when the golden light hits the vines. The architecture of the property feels rustic yet classy, and there are enough cozy spots to sit and relax for hours. Their café and restaurant spaces have a relaxed charm, offering a variety of vegetarian options, though I wish there were more innovative dishes on the menu for non-drinkers like me. Still, the wood-fired pizza and cheese platter were surprisingly good.

What I liked most was how the place isn’t just about wine—it’s about the experience. Even without a wine-tasting session, there was enough to explore and enjoy. The gift shop is great for souvenirs, and the staff were courteous and didn’t pressure us into taking any tours we weren’t interested in.

Overall, Sula was more about the peaceful escape, the vibes, and the views than the wine itself for me. I’d recommend it to anyone looking for a scenic day trip or a calm weekend break—even if you’re not into wine, there’s still something beautiful to take away from the experience.

Sula Vineyards is undeniably beautiful—rolling vineyards, scenic views, and a relaxing ambiance make it a lovely getaway from the city. The grounds are well-maintained, and the overall atmosphere feels upscale and curated for a pleasant day out.

That said, it’s very expensive for what you get. Wine tastings, food, and even basic experiences are priced at a premium, and not always justified by the quality. It feels more commercial than authentic at times, catering heavily to tourists rather than wine enthusiasts.

Worth a visit for the views and photos, but go in knowing it’s more about the setting than the wine itself.

Recently visited Sula Vineyard and what an amazing experience it was! Whether you’re with friends, family or just looking for a refreshing escape from the city, this place is so worth it. Just a few hours from Pune or Mumbai, it makes for a perfect weekend getaway.

The estate is absolutely picturesque, straight out of a Pinterest board. Sprawling greenery, aesthetic spots and those giant wine bottles in the fields are a photo op you just can’t miss!

The wine tasting session was one of the highlights — fun, informative and a great way to understand the craft behind every glass. The cover charge is ₹600 per person, which you can redeem for wine tasting, purchases at the gift shop or even buying a bottle of your favorite wine 🍾.

They also have an in-house restaurant, so you can sip, savor and soak in the vineyard vibes all in one place.

Insider tip: The best time to visit is January to April. That’s when the vineyard is lush with grapes and you might even get to try grape stomping 🍇 (a total bucket list moment!)

All in all, this one’s a must-visit. We loved every bit of it and would definitely recommend planning your visit during the harvest season for the full experience.

A Fascinating Visit to Sula Vineyards — Even Without Tasting the Wine!

I visited Sula Vineyards in Nashik not as a wine enthusiast, but purely out of curiosity to explore how wine is made — and I must say, the visit was truly fascinating and worth every minute! 🍇🍷

From the moment you enter the vineyard, you’re greeted with lush green surroundings, scenic beauty, and a calm, nature-blessed environment. The vineyard tour is well-structured and informative, covering every step — from the cultivation of grapes to the fermentation, bottling, and storage of wine. Even though I didn’t taste any wine (as I don’t drink), I could still appreciate the effort, passion, and precision that goes into the entire winemaking process.

The tour guides were friendly, professional, and explained everything in a simple, engaging manner. The infrastructure and cleanliness of the place is commendable. They maintain the estate with great care, offering a very photogenic and serene atmosphere. There are also souvenir and gift shops, and a peaceful outdoor area to relax.

The only reason I’m giving 4 stars instead of 5 is because for non-wine drinkers like me, the tour could be a bit more engaging — maybe they can add something like grape juice tasting or more interactive experiences beyond just wine sampling.

Overall, even without touching a drop of wine, I had a memorable, educational, and enjoyable experience at Sula. Highly recommended for tourists, photographers, and anyone curious about the art behind India’s leading wine brand.

Sula Vineyards is a beautiful place to visit, but the pricing feels a bit steep. The entry fee is ₹600 on weekdays and ₹1,000 on weekends, which seems high. However, the good part is that this amount can be used as cash/coupons inside, whether at the gift shop, restaurant, wine shop, or for the tour and wine tasting.
That said, the wine-making tour and tasting itself cost ₹700, which is quite expensive, leaving little balance from the entry fee for other expenses. The tour lasts about 20 minutes and ends with a tasting of six different wines.
Inside, the place is well-maintained, with many great spots for clicking pictures. The parking area is spacious and well-managed. However, the Indian cuisine at their restaurant was not up to the mark—perhaps Italian would be a better choice. Overall, it’s a nice experience, but they could reconsider their pricing.

The Shree Kalaram Mandir in Panchavati, Nashik, is one of the most historically and spiritually significant temples in Maharashtra. Built in the 18th century by Sardar Odhekar of the Maratha Empire, this temple is dedicated to Lord Rama, whose idol sculpted in black stone (hence the name "Kalaram") is enshrined here alongside Sita and Lakshmana.

What makes this temple truly stand out is its exceptional architecture. The entire structure is crafted from black basalt stone, with intricate carvings visible on every pillar, arch, and dome. Its towering spires, symmetrical design, and solid stone construction reflect the brilliance of Maratha-era temple craftsmanship. The spacious courtyard and calm atmosphere make it a serene spiritual destination.

Devotees of Lord Ram, especially those following the Bhakti tradition, consider this temple sacred and soul-soothing. Even with the crowd, the temple maintains a peaceful and well-kept environment. A brief historical guide or signage could add to the visitor experience.

A monumental gem of stone architecture, Shree Kalaram Mandir is not just a place of devotion but also a celebration of India's rich cultural and spiritual heritage.

Kalaram Temple is one of the most revered and historic temples in Nashik, located in the sacred Panchavati area. The temple holds immense significance, both spiritually and historically, especially for devotees of Lord Rama.

The temple is dedicated to Lord Rama, and the name "Kalaram" comes from the black stone idol of Lord Rama enshrined here. The idols of Lord Rama, Sita, and Lakshmana are all carved from black stone, adding a majestic aura to the sanctum. The spiritual energy in the temple is palpable — you can instantly feel a sense of calm and devotion upon entering.

Architecture & Ambiance:
Built in 1788 by Sardar Rangarao Odhekar, the temple is a marvelous example of 18th-century Maratha architecture. The black stone structure and the intricately carved pillars are awe-inspiring. The temple premises are well-maintained and spacious, with a peaceful environment ideal for meditation and prayer.

Religious Significance:
Kalaram Mandir is believed to be the exact place where Lord Rama lived during his exile. Panchavati is full of mythological importance, and visiting Kalaram Temple completes the spiritual circuit of Nashik. There’s also the Sita Gufa nearby, which is another must-visit spot tied to the Ramayana.

Festivals and Rituals:
The temple is especially vibrant during Ram Navami, when thousands of devotees visit for darshan. Regular aartis and bhajans are performed, creating a devotional atmosphere. Many devotees tie sacred threads near the temple premises, praying for wishes to come true.

Surroundings:
Located on the banks of the Godavari River, the area around the temple is bustling yet spiritual. Vendors selling flowers, prasad, and religious items line the street. Don’t miss the nearby Kapaleshwar Mahadev and the ancient Godavari Ghats — all within walking distance.

Overall, Kalaram Temple is not just a temple — it's an emotional, historical, and spiritual journey. A must-visit for anyone traveling to Nashik or tracing the footsteps of Lord Rama.

I reached Nashik Road station in the evening, and overall it was a good experience. The station has four platforms, and all basic facilities like toilets, drinking water, sitting arrangements, and even automatic lifts for going up and down are available. It was my first time traveling from Mumbai to Nashik. On the way, just before reaching Igatpuri, I happened to look outside — and honestly, it was an amazing sight. The train passes through tunnels and between two hills — it was such a peaceful and thrilling experience at the same time.

Truly, it was a great, great, great journey — one I’ll remember for a long time.
